t the world if all we know are our ideas?Comprised of eleven previously unpublished essays by leading scholars in the field, Reexamining Berkeley?s Philosophy demonstrates how things in the world are intrinsically related to the sequence of experiences that constitute minds. This collection also discusses how the harmony of experience reveals strategies for recognizing the inherently active character of reality. Ultimately, this volume represents a major contribution to the study of Berkeley?s philosophy by critiquing the tendency to generalize his thought as a version of theologically modified solipsism. In this way, it is a unique and invaluable addition to Berkeley scholarship.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aIdea (Philosophy). 0aIdealism. 0aRealism. 0aThought and thinking. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Discrimination & Race Relations.2bisacsh1 aAyers, Michael R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBelfrage, Bertil, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBreidert, Wolfgang, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCummins, Phillip D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDaniel, Stephen H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGlauser, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHight, Marc A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJaffro, Laurent, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJakapi, Roomet, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMigely, Genevieve, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPappas, George S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchumacher, Ralph, econtributor.4ctb